1133
00:17:07,480 --> 00:17:11,380
Simple assumption. Chronological proximity equals spatial proximity.

1134
00:17:11,600 --> 00:17:14,600
Meaning if they were taken at the same time, they were probably taken in the same place.

1135
00:17:14,600 --> 00:17:19,160
Exactly. If you were walking around the fountain at a steady pace recording a video,

1136
00:17:19,640 --> 00:17:25,420
frame number 150 was physically captured a fraction of a second after frame 149 and just before frame 151.

1137
00:17:25,720 --> 00:17:32,760
Because of that timeline, frame 150 and 151 are basically guaranteed to share a massive percentage of their visual features.

1138
00:17:32,760 --> 00:17:38,580
They are looking at the exact same patch of concrete from maybe a millimeter apart.

1139
00:17:38,780 --> 00:17:45,620
Right. So sequential matching tells the software, hey, do not bother comparing frame 150 to frame 800.

1140
00:17:46,120 --> 00:17:49,960
Just check the five frames immediately before it and the five frames immediately after it.

1141
00:17:50,100 --> 00:17:53,220
That is brilliant. It dramatically slashes the workload.

1142
00:17:53,340 --> 00:17:55,500
The massive N squared problem just vanishes.

1143
00:17:55,840 --> 00:18:01,800
And it's replaced by a highly efficient localized search window that physically follows the path you walk.

1144
00:18:01,800 --> 00:18:02,640
Extremely fast.

1145
00:18:02,760 --> 00:18:05,860
But there is a catch with sequential matching in the real world.

1146
00:18:06,060 --> 00:18:09,300
I was just thinking about this. Let's say I'm walking around the fountain recording my video.

1147
00:18:09,620 --> 00:18:11,580
Halfway through the loop, a dog runs past me.

1148
00:18:11,820 --> 00:18:17,160
I instinctively turn around, point the camera totally away from the fountain, film the dog for 10 seconds,

1149
00:18:17,380 --> 00:18:19,740
and then turn back to the fountain to finish my loop.

1150
00:18:19,840 --> 00:18:23,380
Yeah, you have completely shattered the chronological logic of the data set.

1151
00:18:23,560 --> 00:18:28,840
Right. Frame 300 is the fountain. Frame 301 is a tree on the opposite side of the park where the dog ran.

1152
00:18:29,300 --> 00:18:30,800
Frame 600 is back to the fountain.

1153
00:18:30,800 --> 00:18:30,920
Right.

1154
00:18:32,760 --> 00:18:36,060
Frame 100 is the tree on the opposite side of the park where the dog ran.

1155
00:18:36,060 --> 00:18:42,540
And the entire 3D model will snap in half because the chain of connections is broken.

1156
00:18:42,740 --> 00:18:46,460
Yes. Frame 1 will never connect to frame 1000 because of that interruption.

1157
00:18:47,320 --> 00:18:49,120
Exhaustive matching is way too slow.

1158
00:18:49,540 --> 00:18:56,320
And sequential matching is incredibly vulnerable to interruptions or just disorganized photo collections.

1159
00:18:56,680 --> 00:19:00,320
Which is why CallMap utilizes a third highly sophisticated strategy.

1160
00:19:01,060 --> 00:19:02,220
The vocab tree.

1161
00:19:02,220 --> 00:19:02,740
The vocab tree.

1162
00:19:02,760 --> 00:19:04,200
The vocabulary tree. I love this one.

1163
00:19:04,300 --> 00:19:07,260
It sounds like natural language processing but applied to visual data.

1164
00:19:07,620 --> 00:19:11,400
The mechanism is conceptually very similar to a search engine index like Google.

1165
00:19:11,920 --> 00:19:16,880
When you select vocab tree matching, the software does a rapid preliminary scan of every image in the folder.

1166
00:19:17,440 --> 00:19:21,400
It doesn't do deep feature matching yet. Instead, it quantizes visual information.

1167
00:19:22,060 --> 00:19:26,740
It summarizes the dominant textures and shapes into a compact list of visual words.

1168
00:19:27,160 --> 00:19:29,520
So it generates an index at the back of the textbook.

1169
00:19:29,520 --> 00:19:32,520
It tags, say, image 50 with visual data.

1170
00:19:32,760 --> 00:19:36,860
Visual words like jagged stone, water ripple, and moss.

1171
00:19:36,860 --> 00:19:37,360
Exactly.

1172
00:19:37,360 --> 00:19:42,360
And when it comes time to find matches for image 50, the software just queries the index.

1173
00:19:42,760 --> 00:19:50,400
It asks the vocab tree to return a list of the top 50 other images in the entire dataset that share those specific visual words.

1174
00:19:50,480 --> 00:19:56,420
Oh wow. So it instantly filters out the 900 irrelevant photos of the sky or the pavement or that dog you filmed.

1175
00:19:56,800 --> 00:20:01,120
And it only performs the heavy intensive feature matching on the most probable candidates.

1176
00:20:01,120 --> 00:20:02,320
It is an incredibly elegant.

1177
00:20:02,760 --> 00:20:06,560
It is an incredibly elegant way to handle massive, totally disorganized ground collections.

1178
00:20:06,920 --> 00:20:07,560
It really is.

1179
00:20:07,840 --> 00:20:11,680
Now, there is actually a fourth matching option in the software called spatial matching,

1180
00:20:11,880 --> 00:20:15,280
but we need to explicitly rule it out for our specific mission today.

1181
00:20:15,420 --> 00:20:16,640
Right. Definitely rule it out.

1182
00:20:16,880 --> 00:20:20,860
Spatial matching relies on the GPS coordinates embedded in the image metadata.

1183
00:20:21,440 --> 00:20:25,320
It matches photos based on where the camera physically reported being on the globe.

1184
00:20:25,580 --> 00:20:28,300
And spatial matching is really the domain of the drone operator.

1185
00:20:28,300 --> 00:20:32,260
An enterprise drone flying in open air with an RTK module,

1186
00:20:32,760 --> 00:20:35,760
records its physical location with millimeter precision.

1187
00:20:36,280 --> 00:20:40,560
The software can safely rely on that metadata to decide which images overlap.

1188
00:20:40,680 --> 00:20:43,520
But down on the ground, GPS is a complete mess.

1189
00:20:43,600 --> 00:20:44,560
It's terrible.

1190
00:20:44,680 --> 00:20:48,840
The signal bounces off tall buildings, creating multi-path errors.

1191
00:20:49,120 --> 00:20:51,720
It gets absorbed by thick tree canopies.

1192
00:20:52,080 --> 00:20:57,680
If you rely on your smartphone's GPS chip to tell ColMap which photos of the fountain are close to each other,

1193
00:20:58,000 --> 00:21:01,880
a bad signal bounce might tell the software you were standing a hundred yards away.

1194
00:21:01,920 --> 00:21:02,720
And then the spatial matching is a mess.

1195
00:21:02,880 --> 00:21:04,640
The spatial logic just completely collapses.

1196
00:21:04,840 --> 00:21:07,480
So for capturing large outdoor spaces from the ground,

1197
00:21:07,680 --> 00:21:13,480
we must rely on the visual evidence through sequential or vocab tree matching, not the satellite data.

1198
00:21:13,680 --> 00:21:14,200
One hundred percent.

1199
00:21:14,400 --> 00:21:16,920
So once your chosen matching strategy is executed,

1200
00:21:17,120 --> 00:21:19,880
the software draws thousands of tentative connections.

1201
00:21:20,080 --> 00:21:25,440
These are literal lines linking a SIFT key point in one image to a highly similar key point in another.

1202
00:21:25,640 --> 00:21:28,400
This raw matching data is notoriously gullible.

1203
00:21:28,600 --> 00:21:30,280
Gullible is the perfect word for it.

1204
00:21:30,480 --> 00:21:32,120
The SIFT algorithm is brilliant at finding

1205
00:21:32,120 --> 00:21:36,360
high contrast, but it has zero common sense.

1206
00:21:36,560 --> 00:21:37,640
Zero.

1207
00:21:37,840 --> 00:21:43,040
Let's step away from the fountain for a second and imagine we're capturing a large historic brick building.

1208
00:21:43,240 --> 00:21:48,320
SIFT extracts thousands of features from the sharp corners of the individual bricks.

1209
00:21:48,520 --> 00:21:52,080
And the algorithm looks at a brick corner on the far left side of the building,

1210
00:21:52,280 --> 00:21:55,320
and it looks at a brick corner on the far right side of the building.

1211
00:21:55,520 --> 00:22:02,040
To SIFT, the texture, the contrast, and the local pixel neighborhood are mathematically identical.

1212
00:22:02,240 --> 00:22:08,760
So the raw matching algorithm enthusiastically draws a strong connection between the left side of the building and the right side of the building.

1213
00:22:08,960 --> 00:22:12,160
It declares then the exact same point in physical space.

1214
00:22:12,360 --> 00:22:16,040
Which is a huge problem, because if CallMap accepts that match,

1215
00:22:16,240 --> 00:22:23,520
it is going to attempt to physically fold the 3D model of the building in half just to force those two bricks to occupy the same coordinates.

1216
00:22:23,720 --> 00:22:24,520
It'll look like a taco.

1217
00:22:24,720 --> 00:22:25,920
Yeah.

1218
00:22:26,120 --> 00:22:31,920
Repetitive patterns, brickwork, modern window grids, chain link fences, even the canopy

1219
00:22:32,120 --> 00:22:36,880
and the highly textured tree will generate thousands of these false positive matches.

1220
00:22:37,080 --> 00:22:39,960
We must sanitize the data before we calculate depth.

1221
00:22:40,160 --> 00:22:43,560
And this critical cleanup phase is called geometric verification.

1222
00:22:43,760 --> 00:22:46,800
The software basically has to test the physics of the matches.

1223
00:22:47,000 --> 00:22:47,320
Right.

1224
00:22:47,520 --> 00:22:51,320
It looks at a pair of images and the hundreds of points connecting them.

1225
00:22:51,520 --> 00:22:53,720
And it uses advanced mathematical models,

1226
00:22:53,920 --> 00:22:58,120
specifically calculating what are called homographies or essential matrices.

1227
00:22:58,320 --> 00:23:00,280
While the linear algebra there is dense,

1228
00:23:00,480 --> 00:23:02,080
the underlying concept is actually

1229
00:23:02,280 --> 00:23:04,320
highly intuitive. Think about it.

1230
00:23:04,520 --> 00:23:09,120
If you take a photo of a flat wall, take one step to your right and take a second photo.

1231
00:23:09,320 --> 00:23:13,480
Every single feature on that wall should shift in your camera frame in a predictable

1232
00:23:13,680 --> 00:23:16,040
uniform direction based on your physical movement.

1233
00:23:16,240 --> 00:23:18,440
Exactly. The whole scene translates together.

1234
00:23:18,640 --> 00:23:22,920
So the geometric verification looks at the collective behavior of the entire web of points.

1235
00:23:23,120 --> 00:23:27,040
Right. So if 99 points shift uniformly to the left,

1236
00:23:27,240 --> 00:23:31,880
but one specific point like our misidentified brick corner moves to the right,

1237
00:23:31,920 --> 00:23:36,040
or jumps to a completely different area of the frame, the math flags it.

1238
00:23:36,240 --> 00:23:40,640
The software basically determines that for that specific brick to actually be

1239
00:23:40,840 --> 00:23:45,840
the same physical object, the camera would have to exist in two different locations simultaneously.

1240
00:23:46,040 --> 00:23:48,440
The movement violates the laws of physics.

1241
00:23:48,640 --> 00:23:50,800
So the software identifies the outlier,

1242
00:23:51,000 --> 00:23:53,800
severs the false connection and just deletes the match.

1243
00:23:54,000 --> 00:23:56,280
It trims the web until only the geometrically

1244
00:23:56,280 --> 00:23:58,480
consistent physically possible connections remain.

1245
00:23:58,680 --> 00:24:01,320
And with that, we have now completed feature extraction and

1246
00:24:01,320 --> 00:24:03,920
correspondence search. We finally have a pristine,

1247
00:24:04,120 --> 00:24:06,960
verified web of relationships between all our photographs.

1248
00:24:07,160 --> 00:24:10,400
But, and this is wild, we are still entirely stuck in two dimensions.

1249
00:24:10,600 --> 00:24:13,560
We haven't calculated a single millimeter of actual depth yet.

1250
00:24:13,760 --> 00:24:17,280
Nope. But we have finally reached the threshold of 3D.

1251
00:24:17,480 --> 00:24:21,200
We enter step four of the pipeline, incremental reconstruction.

1252
00:24:21,400 --> 00:24:24,520
This is where the physical world is actually born from the flat data.

1253
00:24:24,720 --> 00:24:28,200
And it requires an incredibly delicate process called initialization.

1254
00:24:28,400 --> 00:24:31,240
Initialization. So the software has to pick a starting point.

1255
00:24:31,440 --> 00:24:33,560
It has to choose two images from the folder,

1256
00:24:33,760 --> 00:24:39,080
calculate the distance to the features they share and plot the very first 3D points in the empty void.

1257
00:24:39,280 --> 00:24:39,880
Right.

1258
00:24:40,080 --> 00:24:44,040
And I think the natural assumption for anyone doing this is that the software

1259
00:24:44,240 --> 00:24:47,760
just grabs image number one and image number two and starts doing the math.

1260
00:24:47,960 --> 00:24:53,080
And that assumption is exactly why many initial attempts at 3D scanning fail.

1261
00:24:53,280 --> 00:24:54,720
For incremental reconstruction,

1262
00:24:54,920 --> 00:24:59,720
starting with two chronologically adjacent images is usually a catastrophic mistake.

1263
00:24:59,920 --> 00:25:00,920
Really? Why?

1264
00:25:01,320 --> 00:25:04,240
It all comes down to the necessity of parallax and baseline.

1265
00:25:04,440 --> 00:25:06,560
OK, let's define the baseline in camera terms.

1266
00:25:06,760 --> 00:25:10,200
The baseline is simply the physical distance between the camera's position

1267
00:25:10,400 --> 00:25:13,000
in the first photo and its position in the second photo.

1268
00:25:13,200 --> 00:25:17,720
Exactly. Now think about walking around the fountain shooting a 60 frame per second video.

1269
00:25:17,920 --> 00:25:22,200
The physical distance you travel between frame one and frame two is perhaps a fraction of an inch.

1270
00:25:22,400 --> 00:25:25,000
Oh, right. So the baseline is virtually non-existent.

1271
00:25:25,200 --> 00:25:27,520
And because the cameras are so close together,

1272
00:25:27,720 --> 00:25:30,040
the perspective shift, the parallax between the two frames,

1273
00:25:30,240 --> 00:25:31,320
is mathematically non-existent.

1274
00:25:31,520 --> 00:25:32,160
So the baseline is negligible.

1275
00:25:32,360 --> 00:25:33,160
Yep.

1276
00:25:33,360 --> 00:25:37,520
If the software tries to calculate the depth of the fountain using two viewpoints

1277
00:25:37,720 --> 00:25:40,840
that are only an inch apart, the math is incredibly weak.

1278
00:25:41,040 --> 00:25:44,320
It's kind of the equivalent of trying to accurately judge the distance of a

1279
00:25:44,320 --> 00:25:47,800
mountain peak 10 miles away by shifting your head a millimeter to the left.

1280
00:25:47,800 --> 00:25:49,040
That's a perfect analogy.

1281
00:25:49,240 --> 00:25:53,040
The resulting 3D points from that tiny baseline will be noisy,

1282
00:25:53,240 --> 00:25:56,720
wildly inaccurate and structurally unsound.

1283
00:25:56,920 --> 00:26:00,240
If you build the rest of the model on that weak foundation,

1284
00:26:00,240 --> 00:26:02,080
the entire reconstruction will fail.

1285
00:26:02,280 --> 00:26:03,200
And the software knows this.

1286
00:26:03,400 --> 00:26:04,480
During initialization,

1287
00:26:04,680 --> 00:26:07,680
CoalMaps scans the entire web of verified matches,

1288
00:26:07,880 --> 00:26:13,040
searching for a pair of images that satisfy two somewhat conflating requirements.

1289
00:26:13,240 --> 00:26:16,720
First, they must share a massive number of verified features,

1290
00:26:16,920 --> 00:26:17,960
so they're strongly linked.

1291
00:26:18,160 --> 00:26:21,960
Second, they must have a very wide physical baseline,

1292
00:26:22,160 --> 00:26:24,000
a drastic change in perspective.

1293
00:26:24,200 --> 00:26:29,280
Which brings us directly back to the specific capture strategy used by the researchers at the Oregon State Capitol.

1294
00:26:29,480 --> 00:26:30,200
When they filmed the

1295
00:26:30,400 --> 00:26:32,440
mountain, they didn't just walk in a single circle.

1296
00:26:32,640 --> 00:26:33,040
No, they didn't.

1297
00:26:33,240 --> 00:26:36,920
They walked one complete loop holding the camera high above their heads.

1298
00:26:37,120 --> 00:26:41,000
Then they lowered the camera to chest level and walked a second complete loop.

1299
00:26:41,200 --> 00:26:46,320
And that vertical shift is the absolute key to successful initialization.

1300
00:26:46,520 --> 00:26:47,960
Because of that strategy,

1301
00:26:48,160 --> 00:26:54,360
CoalMaps searches the data and totally bypasses the weak connection between frame one and frame two.

1302
00:26:54,560 --> 00:26:59,280
Instead, it might select frame one from the very beginning of the overhead loop,

1303
00:26:59,440 --> 00:27:02,280
and frame one from the very beginning of the overhead loop.

1304
00:27:02,480 --> 00:27:05,240
So, the software has a perfect stereoscopic foundation.

1305
00:27:05,440 --> 00:27:11,280
It uses that wide perspective shift to triangulate the depth of those shared features with extremely high mathematical confidence.

1306
00:27:11,480 --> 00:27:12,080
Right.

1307
00:27:12,280 --> 00:27:14,440
It plots that first cluster of images,

1308
00:27:14,640 --> 00:27:17,440
and then it takes the data from the first cluster of images,

1309
00:27:17,640 --> 00:27:20,440
and then it takes the data from the second cluster of images,

1310
00:27:20,640 --> 00:27:23,440
and then it takes the data from the third cluster of images,

1311
00:27:23,640 --> 00:27:27,440
and then it takes the data from the fourth cluster of images,

1312
00:27:27,440 --> 00:27:29,560
and then it takes the data from the fifth cluster of images.

1313
00:27:29,760 --> 00:27:30,560
Right.

1314
00:27:30,760 --> 00:27:33,360
It plots that first cluster of 3D points into the void.

1315
00:27:33,560 --> 00:27:34,840
The foundation is solidly set.

1316
00:27:35,040 --> 00:27:38,120
Now, the incremental part of the reconstruction truly begins.

1317
00:27:38,320 --> 00:27:39,680
The incremental loop. How does that work?

1318
00:27:39,880 --> 00:27:43,400
The software enters this continuous rigorous cycle.

1319
00:27:43,600 --> 00:27:46,640
It looks at the small cluster of 3D points it just generated.

1320
00:27:46,840 --> 00:27:50,800
Then it searches the remaining 2D images for a third photo

1321
00:27:51,000 --> 00:27:54,400
that shares SIFT features with those existing 3D points.

1322
00:27:54,600 --> 00:27:55,400
Okay. It finds an overlapping image.

1323
00:27:55,600 --> 00:27:57,400
Now, it has to figure out where that third camera was actually set.

1324
00:27:55,600 --> 00:27:56,400
That's right.

1325
00:27:56,560 --> 00:27:59,200
The third camera was actually standing in physical space.

1326
00:27:59,400 --> 00:28:02,760
It executes a mathematical process called image registration.

1327
00:28:02,960 --> 00:28:08,480
Yeah. And the underlying math here is known as the perspective endpoint problem, or PNP.

1328
00:28:08,680 --> 00:28:14,440
The software analyzes how the known 3D points project onto the flat 2D sensor of the new image.

1329
00:28:14,640 --> 00:28:19,480
And by reversing that projection, it calculates the exact physical XYZ coordinates

1330
00:28:19,680 --> 00:28:22,240
and the rotation of that third camera in the virtual space.

1331
00:28:22,440 --> 00:28:25,560
Once it anchors that third camera, it uses that new vantage point

1332
00:28:25,720 --> 00:28:28,360
to look at other features in the image, calculates their depth,

1333
00:28:28,560 --> 00:28:30,600
and plots even more 3D points into the void.

1334
00:28:30,800 --> 00:28:32,480
And that process is called triangulation.

1335
00:28:32,680 --> 00:28:33,480
The model grows.

1336
00:28:33,680 --> 00:28:36,960
Then it finds a fourth overlapping image, registers the fourth camera,

1337
00:28:37,160 --> 00:28:40,080
triangulates more points than a fifth, then a tenth, then a hundredth.

1338
00:28:40,280 --> 00:28:42,880
Camera by camera, point by point,

1339
00:28:43,080 --> 00:28:46,880
the geometry of the fountain is slowly pulled out of the darkness and assembled.

1340
00:28:47,080 --> 00:28:48,880
It is a phenomenal process,

1341
00:28:49,080 --> 00:28:52,360
but honestly, it immediately raises a massive red flag for me.

1342
00:28:52,480 --> 00:28:54,520
The drift. Yes, the drift.

1343
00:28:54,520 --> 00:28:56,920
If it is building this entire world sequentially,

1344
00:28:57,120 --> 00:29:01,880
if camera four derives its position from camera three and camera five derives

1345
00:29:02,080 --> 00:29:06,400
from camera four, we are essentially dealing with a mathematical telephone game.

1346
00:29:06,600 --> 00:29:11,280
And error accumulation is the single most dangerous threat to an incremental pipeline.

1347
00:29:11,480 --> 00:29:15,160
Let's say the calculation for camera three is off by just a microscopic fraction

1348
00:29:15,360 --> 00:29:18,920
of a degree due to sensor noise or a slightly blurry pixel.

1349
00:29:19,120 --> 00:29:23,680
Camera four bases its entire reality on camera three, so it inherits that tiny error,

1350
00:29:23,680 --> 00:29:27,400
and inevitably adds its own microscopic miscalculation on top.

1351
00:29:27,600 --> 00:29:28,160
Exactly.

1352
00:29:28,360 --> 00:29:32,200
And by the time the software registers camera 1000 on the opposite side of the fountain,

1353
00:29:32,400 --> 00:29:35,160
those microscopic errors have compounded exponentially.

1354
00:29:35,360 --> 00:29:36,880
The fountain would physically twist.

1355
00:29:37,080 --> 00:29:39,760
The start of the loop would never align with the end of the loop.

1356
00:29:39,960 --> 00:29:42,880
If the software merely added cameras blindly,

1357
00:29:43,080 --> 00:29:47,200
the result would always be a warped, unusable mess.

1358
00:29:47,400 --> 00:29:53,080
So to combat this drift, Colomap constantly employs a rigorous optimization algorithm

1359
00:29:53,680 --> 00:29:55,360
known as bundle adjustment.

1360
00:29:55,560 --> 00:29:56,560
Bundle adjustment.

1361
00:29:56,760 --> 00:30:01,280
The terminology in this field is so dense, but the concept is actually very physical.

1362
00:30:01,480 --> 00:30:03,160
When I first hear bundle adjustment,

1363
00:30:03,360 --> 00:30:07,680
I picture someone trying to carry a massive, overflowing armful of firewood.

1364
00:30:07,880 --> 00:30:08,680
That's a good visual.

1365
00:30:08,880 --> 00:30:13,240
A log starts slipping, the balance shifts, and the person has to momentarily stop

1366
00:30:13,440 --> 00:30:16,880
walking, shuffle the logs around, and aggressively tighten their grip

1367
00:30:17,080 --> 00:30:19,880
on the entire bundle so it doesn't all collapse onto the ground.

1368
00:30:20,080 --> 00:30:22,200
What is actually being bundled in the software?

1369
00:30:22,400 --> 00:30:23,400
The metaphor aligns perfectly

1370
00:30:23,400 --> 00:30:24,520
with the math, honestly.

1371
00:30:24,720 --> 00:30:28,120
The bundle refers to the dense web of mathematical viewing rays,

1372
00:30:28,320 --> 00:30:31,720
the invisible lines connecting every calculated camera position

1373
00:30:31,920 --> 00:30:34,280
to every triangulated 3D point in the space.

1374
00:30:34,480 --> 00:30:34,760
OK.

1375
00:30:34,960 --> 00:30:38,960
Bundle adjustment is the mathematical process of simultaneously tweaking

1376
00:30:39,160 --> 00:30:44,440
the positions of the cameras and the 3D points to minimize the tension and error in that web.

1377
00:30:44,640 --> 00:30:48,240
So the software is actively tightening its grip on the geometry,

1378
00:30:48,440 --> 00:30:52,280
and the source details two specific flavors of this optimization.

1379
00:30:52,480 --> 00:30:53,320
Local bundle

1380
00:30:53,520 --> 00:30:55,600
adjustment and global bundle adjustment.

1381
00:30:55,800 --> 00:30:58,440
Local bundle adjustment happens continuously.

1382
00:30:58,640 --> 00:31:03,640
Every single time Cullmap adds a new image and triangulates new points,

1383
00:31:03,840 --> 00:31:06,640
it pauses and runs a local adjustment.

1384
00:31:06,840 --> 00:31:10,200
But crucially, it does not recalculate the entire scene.

1385
00:31:10,400 --> 00:31:12,880
It only adjusts the firewood that is actively slipping.

1386
00:31:13,080 --> 00:31:16,640
So if the software just registered camera 800 on the north face of the fountain,

1387
00:31:16,840 --> 00:31:19,840
adjusting the cameras on the far south face won't help anything.

1388
00:31:20,040 --> 00:31:22,920
Exactly. The software isolates the immediate neighborhood,

1389
00:31:23,040 --> 00:31:26,000
the newly added camera and the cameras directly connected to it,

1390
00:31:26,200 --> 00:31:30,560
and runs a rapid optimization algorithm, usually something like Levenberg-Marcourt.

1391
00:31:30,760 --> 00:31:34,040
It subtly shifts the local points to minimize the immediate error.

1392
00:31:34,240 --> 00:31:38,480
It is a fast, efficient way to keep the local geometry tight as the model expands.

1393
00:31:38,680 --> 00:31:42,280
But local adjustments cannot solve the overarching systematic drift

1394
00:31:42,480 --> 00:31:45,440
that slowly bows the entire model over hundreds of frames.

1395
00:31:45,640 --> 00:31:49,280
Eventually, the software must reckon with the entire data set at once.

1396
00:31:49,480 --> 00:31:52,040
That is when it triggers a global bundle adjustment.

1397
00:31:52,040 --> 00:31:54,960
The software stops adding new images entirely.

1398
00:31:55,160 --> 00:31:58,920
It takes the entire bundle, every single camera pose it has calculated,

1399
00:31:59,120 --> 00:32:03,680
and hundreds of thousands of 3D points and essentially drops them all onto the floor.

1400
00:32:03,880 --> 00:32:06,280
And then it runs a massive computationally

1401
00:32:06,480 --> 00:32:09,880
punishing optimization across the entire model simultaneously,

1402
00:32:10,080 --> 00:32:14,560
forcing every single point into the most mathematically cohesive shape possible.

1403
00:32:14,760 --> 00:32:17,640
It totally eradicates the telephone game error.

1404
00:32:17,840 --> 00:32:21,840
But the source highlights a truly brilliant aspect of this global

1405
00:32:21,840 --> 00:32:26,560
optimization. The software isn't just tweaking the physical locations of the cameras.

1406
00:32:26,760 --> 00:32:31,440
It actively interrogates the camera model parameters we defined way back in step one.

1407
00:32:31,640 --> 00:32:35,840
Wait, remember the K1 and K2 radial distortion numbers we fed it for our wide angle lens?

1408
00:32:36,040 --> 00:32:39,000
Yes, exactly. During a global bundle adjustment,

1409
00:32:39,200 --> 00:32:43,120
the software looks at the massive amount of 3D evidence it's compiled and realizes,

1410
00:32:43,320 --> 00:32:46,880
hey, if I adjust my assumption about the physical curvature of the glass lens by

1411
00:32:47,080 --> 00:32:50,880
just 1%, the geometric error across the entire fountain drops dramatically.

1412
00:32:51,080 --> 00:32:51,840
That's insane.

1413
00:32:52,040 --> 00:32:56,560
The software refined its understanding of the physical lens based on the reality

1414
00:32:56,760 --> 00:32:58,240
of the 3D world it is building.

1415
00:32:58,440 --> 00:33:02,240
The model continuously teaches the software how to see it better.

1416
00:33:02,440 --> 00:33:04,960
It is a breathtaking feedback loop. It really is.

1417
00:33:05,160 --> 00:33:10,040
But this incredible, meticulous step by step process, registering a camera,

1418
00:33:10,240 --> 00:33:14,840
triangulating, local adjustment, global adjustment, leads us directly into the most

1419
00:33:15,040 --> 00:33:18,320
notorious frustration for anyone attempting 3D reconstruction.

1420
00:33:18,520 --> 00:33:20,080
It is the hardware bottleneck.

1421
00:33:20,280 --> 00:33:20,720
Yes.

