1430
00:33:43,240 --> 00:33:46,120
But then incremental reconstruction begins.

1431
00:33:46,320 --> 00:33:48,680
The progress bar crawls to a total halt.

1432
00:33:48,880 --> 00:33:51,440
The software estimates it will take five hours to finish.

1433
00:33:51,960 --> 00:33:56,800
The user checks their system monitor and their hyper expensive GPU is sitting at maybe 4% utilization,

1434
00:33:57,000 --> 00:33:59,800
while their standard CPU is maxed out and overheating.

1435
00:34:00,000 --> 00:34:05,200
Why is the actual birth of the 3D model barely using the graphics card?

1436
00:34:05,400 --> 00:34:06,920
To understand that bottleneck,

1437
00:34:07,120 --> 00:34:10,040
you really have to look at the fundamental architectural differences

1438
00:34:10,240 --> 00:34:13,360
between how a GPU and a CPU solve problems.

1439
00:34:13,560 --> 00:34:16,240
The source material provides a fantastic framework for this.

1440
00:34:16,440 --> 00:34:19,200
Think of the computational workload as a police search.

1441
00:34:19,400 --> 00:34:20,960
A GPU is structured like an army

1442
00:34:20,960 --> 00:34:22,800
of a million rookie cops.

1443
00:34:23,000 --> 00:34:26,120
Right. They have very small amounts of memory processes.

1444
00:34:26,320 --> 00:34:29,680
VRAM limitations are a massive factor in 3D processing.

1445
00:34:29,880 --> 00:34:33,640
And their internal architecture, the ALUs, are designed for very simple math.

1446
00:34:33,840 --> 00:34:37,080
So you line up your million rookies across a massive field and you tell them,

1447
00:34:37,280 --> 00:34:40,400
everyone take one step forward, stare at the single square inch of grass

1448
00:34:40,400 --> 00:34:42,520
in front of your boots and shout if you see a clue.

1449
00:34:42,720 --> 00:34:44,920
The task is massively parallelized.

1450
00:34:45,120 --> 00:34:50,080
Millions of simple independent operations executing simultaneously.

1451
00:34:50,080 --> 00:34:54,440
That is exactly why feature extraction is so incredibly fast on a GPU.

1452
00:34:54,640 --> 00:34:59,280
Finding a high contrast sift blob in the top left corner of an image has absolutely

1453
00:34:59,480 --> 00:35:03,080
zero mathematical dependency on finding a blob in the bottom right corner.

1454
00:35:03,280 --> 00:35:05,760
The million rookies scan the grid instantly,

1455
00:35:05,960 --> 00:35:08,120
but incremental reconstruction is not a search.

1456
00:35:08,320 --> 00:35:11,040
It is an unfolding, highly complex sequence.

1457
00:35:11,040 --> 00:35:12,560
You cannot parallelize a sequence.

1458
00:35:12,560 --> 00:35:14,480
You cannot register camera five until

1459
00:35:14,480 --> 00:35:17,240
the underlying math for camera four is definitively locked in.

1460
00:35:17,440 --> 00:35:19,920
And camera four depends on camera three.

1461
00:35:20,120 --> 00:35:22,600
If you have a million rookie cops to solve a sequential murder mystery,

1462
00:35:22,800 --> 00:35:24,440
the investigation collapses.

1463
00:35:24,640 --> 00:35:29,520
Rookie number 500 cannot do his job because he is waiting for rookie 499 to hand him the evidence.

1464
00:35:29,520 --> 00:35:30,760
You don't need an army of rookies.

1465
00:35:30,960 --> 00:35:32,760
You need a single master detective.

1466
00:35:32,960 --> 00:35:34,080
And that is the CPU.

1467
00:35:34,280 --> 00:35:35,800
A CPU doesn't have thousands of cores.

1468
00:35:36,000 --> 00:35:38,560
It has eight, sixteen or maybe twenty four.

1469
00:35:38,760 --> 00:35:41,600
But each of those cores is vastly more sophisticated.

1470
00:35:41,800 --> 00:35:45,440
They have access to massive amounts of system RAM and they are engineered to solve

1471
00:35:45,640 --> 00:35:50,040
intense, deeply convoluted linear algebra equations step by step without stalling.

1472
00:35:50,240 --> 00:35:52,760
So the CPU is the master detective,

1473
00:35:52,960 --> 00:35:57,360
meticulously solving the localized and global bundle adjustments,

1474
00:35:57,560 --> 00:36:00,520
unspooling the mathematical knot one camera at a time.

1475
00:36:00,720 --> 00:36:04,800
The heavy lifting of incremental 3D reconstruction is fundamentally,

1476
00:36:05,000 --> 00:36:07,040
inherently a CPU bound process.

1477
00:36:07,240 --> 00:36:10,200
You simply have to wait for the detective to finish the work.

1478
00:36:10,400 --> 00:36:13,560
That structural reality is deeply satisfying to understand,

1479
00:36:13,760 --> 00:36:17,920
but it doesn't really change the fact that five hours is a long time to wait for a model.

1480
00:36:17,960 --> 00:36:19,320
It is a very long time.

1481
00:36:19,320 --> 00:36:20,000
What if you need to

1482
00:36:20,120 --> 00:36:25,800
process thousands of ground images and you cannot afford the CPU bottleneck?

1483
00:36:26,000 --> 00:36:30,800
What if there is a way to entirely skip the slow sequential detective work?

1484
00:36:31,000 --> 00:36:34,240
Which brings us to the bleeding edge of the source material and the introduction

1485
00:36:34,440 --> 00:36:36,640
of an alternative pipeline called GLOMAP.

1486
00:36:36,840 --> 00:36:39,680
GLMAP, that stands for Global Mapper.

1487
00:36:39,880 --> 00:36:40,840
And fascinatingly,

1488
00:36:40,840 --> 00:36:43,360
Johannes Schoenberger, the original architect of the incremental

1489
00:36:43,560 --> 00:36:47,320
Coal Map, was deeply involved in developing this new approach just recently.

1490
00:36:47,520 --> 00:36:47,800
Yes.

1491
00:36:48,000 --> 00:36:49,960
He recognized the unavoidable CPU

1492
00:36:50,160 --> 00:36:53,600
bottleneck of his own software and helped engineer a fundamentally different

1493
00:36:53,800 --> 00:36:54,680
mathematical strategy.

1494
00:36:54,880 --> 00:36:56,440
So how does GLOMAP differ?

1495
00:36:56,640 --> 00:37:00,160
GLOMAP abandons the sequential foundation entirely.

1496
00:37:00,360 --> 00:37:02,480
It does not initialize a starting pair.

1497
00:37:02,680 --> 00:37:05,320
It does not build the model one camera at a time.

1498
00:37:05,520 --> 00:37:08,160
It attempts the incredibly audacious task

1499
00:37:08,360 --> 00:37:13,040
of solving the position of every single camera in the entire dataset simultaneously.

1500
00:37:13,240 --> 00:37:15,560
Wait, how is that mathematically possible?

1501
00:37:15,760 --> 00:37:19,920
If you throw a thousand unstructured ground images into the void all at once,

1502
00:37:20,120 --> 00:37:24,520
how can the software possibly organize them without a step by step baseline?

1503
00:37:24,720 --> 00:37:26,400
It splits the pose estimation into two

1504
00:37:26,600 --> 00:37:30,480
distinct phases, relying heavily on a concept called rotation averaging.

1505
00:37:30,680 --> 00:37:32,280
OK, rotation averaging.

1506
00:37:32,280 --> 00:37:35,680
Now we still run the initial feature extraction and correspondence search.

1507
00:37:35,880 --> 00:37:39,600
We still need that verified web of 2D matches connecting the images.

1508
00:37:39,600 --> 00:37:41,480
Right. So we know what photos share features.

1509
00:37:41,480 --> 00:37:44,280
We just don't know where the photos belong in physical 3D space.

1510
00:37:44,480 --> 00:37:47,960
Exactly. But instead of trying to find the XYZ location right away,

1511
00:37:48,160 --> 00:37:49,960
GLOMAP looks at everything in the 3D space.

1512
00:37:50,160 --> 00:37:53,200
It calculates every single pair of ratched images and performs a rapid

1513
00:37:53,400 --> 00:37:56,440
calculation to estimate only the relative rotation between them.

1514
00:37:56,640 --> 00:37:58,560
It ignores physical distance entirely.

1515
00:37:58,760 --> 00:38:00,560
Completely ignores distance.

1516
00:38:00,760 --> 00:38:04,360
It simply asks, how much did the photographer tilt or pan

1517
00:38:04,560 --> 00:38:06,880
the lens between photo A and photo B?

1518
00:38:07,000 --> 00:38:09,440
So it only cares about the direction the camera was pointing.

1519
00:38:09,640 --> 00:38:13,360
It calculates thousands of these isolated rotational guesses.

1520
00:38:13,560 --> 00:38:15,120
Then it throws all those relative

1521
00:38:15,320 --> 00:38:19,120
rotations into a massive global optimization algorithm.

1522
00:38:19,280 --> 00:38:21,880
The software searches for a single unified

1523
00:38:22,080 --> 00:38:26,880
orientation framework that satisfies as many of those individual guesses as possible.

1524
00:38:27,080 --> 00:38:30,440
Oh, I see. And because it is only solving for rotation,

1525
00:38:30,640 --> 00:38:34,320
the math is significantly less complex than a full bundle adjustment.

1526
00:38:34,520 --> 00:38:37,080
And it can actually leverage much more parallel processing.

1527
00:38:37,280 --> 00:38:39,400
Exactly. It gets every single camera pointing

1528
00:38:39,400 --> 00:38:43,320
in the correct direction relative to each other all at the exact same time.

1529
00:38:43,520 --> 00:38:46,520
But they are still just floating haphazardly in space.

1530
00:38:46,720 --> 00:38:48,440
The actual geometry doesn't exist yet.

1531
00:38:48,440 --> 00:38:52,720
Once the global rotation is locked, it initiates the global positioning step.

1532
00:38:52,920 --> 00:38:54,880
The algorithm slides all those properly

1533
00:38:54,880 --> 00:38:58,320
oriented cameras along their mathematical viewing rays, shifting them through the

1534
00:38:58,520 --> 00:39:02,120
void until the thousands of 2D feature matches all converge and intersect

1535
00:39:02,320 --> 00:39:03,960
on cohesive 3D points in the center.

1536
00:39:04,160 --> 00:39:08,840
It pulls the entire chaotic web tight in one massive movement.

1537
00:39:09,040 --> 00:39:12,600
The model basically pops into existence almost instantly.

1538
00:39:12,800 --> 00:39:14,920
The source notes that Geolab operates at

1539
00:39:15,120 --> 00:39:18,400
speeds that make incremental reconstruction look archaic.

1540
00:39:18,600 --> 00:39:22,720
But a shortcut that aggressive obviously comes with severe limitations.

1541
00:39:22,920 --> 00:39:24,000
Oh, absolutely.

1542
00:39:24,200 --> 00:39:26,240
When we look at our specific mission today,

1543
00:39:26,440 --> 00:39:32,040
capturing large outdoor spaces from the ground, Geolab is a high risk, high reward gamble.

1544
00:39:32,240 --> 00:39:33,320
Why is it high risk?

1545
00:39:33,520 --> 00:39:37,360
It requires an incredibly specific type of data collection to succeed.

1546
00:39:37,560 --> 00:39:40,520
Geolab demands a highly interconnected data set.

1547
00:39:40,720 --> 00:39:42,320
It thrives on loop closures.

1548
00:39:42,520 --> 00:39:44,880
Loop closures. Let's go back to the fountain example.

1549
00:39:45,080 --> 00:39:48,000
The videographer walked a complete circle around the structure, returning

1550
00:39:48,600 --> 00:39:50,400
a the exact patch of sidewalk where they started.

1551
00:39:50,600 --> 00:39:51,640
That is a loop closure, right?

1552
00:39:51,640 --> 00:39:51,920
Yes.

1553
00:39:52,120 --> 00:39:53,600
Because the end of the image sequence

1554
00:39:53,600 --> 00:39:55,880
physically overlaps with the beginning of the sequence,

1555
00:39:56,080 --> 00:40:00,280
the 2D matching web is incredibly dense and structurally found.

1556
00:40:00,480 --> 00:40:02,480
Geolab uses the strength of that closed

1557
00:40:02,680 --> 00:40:07,200
loop to anchor the global rotation map, pulling the entire fountain into perfect focus.

1558
00:40:07,400 --> 00:40:09,840
But consider a different outdoor capture.

1559
00:40:10,040 --> 00:40:14,000
Let's say I want to 3D model the storefronts on a historic main street.

1560
00:40:14,200 --> 00:40:17,600
I hold my camera and I walk straight down the sidewalk for 10 blocks,

1561
00:40:17,600 --> 00:40:20,360
capturing the facades as I go, and then I just stop.

1562
00:40:20,560 --> 00:40:22,160
I never turn around. I never walk back.

1563
00:40:22,160 --> 00:40:22,960
I never close the loop.

1564
00:40:23,160 --> 00:40:26,400
Straight line capture creates a brittle mathematical chain.

1565
00:40:26,600 --> 00:40:28,640
Frame one shares features with frame five.

1566
00:40:28,840 --> 00:40:30,360
Frame five connects to frame ten.

1567
00:40:30,560 --> 00:40:32,560
But frame one has absolutely zero

1568
00:40:32,760 --> 00:40:36,720
mathematical relationship to frame 1000 at the far end of the block.

1569
00:40:36,920 --> 00:40:38,880
The global web is incredibly weak.

1570
00:40:38,920 --> 00:40:40,880
If you feed that straight line data set

1571
00:40:40,880 --> 00:40:44,160
into Geolab, the global positioning math just collapses, doesn't it?

1572
00:40:44,160 --> 00:40:45,560
It cannot resolve the tension.

1573
00:40:45,760 --> 00:40:47,560
And the source describes the failure

1574
00:40:47,760 --> 00:40:50,320
of the state of Geolab and it is fascinatingly chaotic.

1575
00:40:50,520 --> 00:40:51,840
It's hilarious, honestly.

1576
00:40:52,040 --> 00:40:56,000
When incremental Geolab fails, it just slowly drifts and bends like a banana.

1577
00:40:56,200 --> 00:40:58,160
When Geolab fails, it panics.

1578
00:40:58,360 --> 00:40:59,760
The visual output is bizarre.

1579
00:40:59,960 --> 00:41:03,440
The source specifically refers to the failures as Borg cubes.

1580
00:41:03,640 --> 00:41:08,080
Borg cubes. Because the software lacks the loop closures to anchor the structure,

1581
00:41:08,280 --> 00:41:12,040
the cameras essentially pull each other into a localized gravitational collapse.

1582
00:41:12,240 --> 00:41:16,760
So instead of a smooth street, the software outputs a dense, glitchy,

1583
00:41:16,920 --> 00:41:21,600
perfectly square cube of overlapping cameras just hovering in empty space.

1584
00:41:21,800 --> 00:41:24,120
The geometry completely destroys itself.

1585
00:41:24,320 --> 00:41:27,240
The model implodes into a singularity.

1586
00:41:27,440 --> 00:41:31,880
But, you know, from a workflow perspective, even that catastrophic failure is highly valuable.

1587
00:41:32,080 --> 00:41:33,400
Because it fails fast.

1588
00:41:33,600 --> 00:41:38,240
You don't wait five hours for a master detective CPU to slowly build a warped,

1589
00:41:38,440 --> 00:41:42,440
unusable street. Geolab hands you a Borg cube in five minutes.

1590
00:41:42,440 --> 00:41:46,040
Right. You instantly know your data set lacks structural integrity.

1591
00:41:46,040 --> 00:41:48,240
So you switch your software back to the slow,

1592
00:41:48,440 --> 00:41:51,960
incremental car map and you let the CPU brute force the straight line.

1593
00:41:52,160 --> 00:41:54,280
Having both tools allows you to attack

1594
00:41:54,280 --> 00:41:57,600
different types of geometry with the appropriate mathematical strategy.

1595
00:41:57,800 --> 00:42:00,560
This is amazing. We have completely demystified the black box.

1596
00:42:00,560 --> 00:42:01,400
You really have.

1597
00:42:01,600 --> 00:42:05,120
We started with the goal of capturing a massive outdoor space without relying

1598
00:42:05,320 --> 00:42:09,160
on the cheat codes of a drone, and we examined how the SIFT algorithm acts

1599
00:42:09,160 --> 00:42:12,360
as the eyes of the pipeline, utilizing difference of the Gaussian's

1600
00:42:12,560 --> 00:42:16,000
to hunt for high contrast scale invariant freckles on the face of the architect.

1601
00:42:16,200 --> 00:42:19,640
Sure. We saw how to blind the software to dynamic

1602
00:42:19,840 --> 00:42:24,120
noise using masks and how to unbend the physical distortion of our lenses.

1603
00:42:24,120 --> 00:42:28,360
By defining the camera model, we explored how sequential and vocab tree matching

1604
00:42:28,560 --> 00:42:32,520
allow us to connect those features without crushing our hardware with N squared

1605
00:42:32,720 --> 00:42:36,960
exhaustive math. We verify the physics of those matches using homographies,

1606
00:42:37,160 --> 00:42:41,840
initialized our models by leveraging the parallax of a wide baseline and watch

1607
00:42:42,040 --> 00:42:46,000
the CPU act as a master detective to incrementally bundle, adjust the

1608
00:42:46,200 --> 00:42:47,320
geometry into reality.

1609
00:42:47,520 --> 00:42:51,400
And we looked at the bleeding edge, utilizing gelo map to instantly snap

1610
00:42:51,600 --> 00:42:55,560
a model together, provided we give it the dense loop closures it craves.

1611
00:42:55,760 --> 00:42:59,160
The theory is profound, but the source material ends with a direct

1612
00:42:59,360 --> 00:43:03,280
call to action, and it is one we definitely must echo to you, the listener.

1613
00:43:03,320 --> 00:43:05,680
Absolutely. Do not leave this knowledge in the abstract.

1614
00:43:05,880 --> 00:43:09,640
Reading about photogrammetry is vastly different from actually executing it.

1615
00:43:09,840 --> 00:43:15,800
Do not just download a pristine, prepackaged, open source data set of a statue where you know the lighting is perfect

1616
00:43:16,200 --> 00:43:18,200
and the model map is guaranteed to solve.

1617
00:43:18,400 --> 00:43:20,880
You have the necessary hardware in your pocket right now.

1618
00:43:21,080 --> 00:43:26,400
Go outside. Find a textured brick building, a local monument or a park fountain.

1619
00:43:26,600 --> 00:43:27,680
Grab your smartphone.

1620
00:43:27,880 --> 00:43:32,680
Walk around the structure, consciously thinking about overlap, texture and parallax.

1621
00:43:32,880 --> 00:43:33,760
Download CalmApp.

1622
00:43:33,960 --> 00:43:37,720
It is entirely free and open source and feed your own photos into the pipeline.

1623
00:43:37,920 --> 00:43:40,680
Watch the feature extraction isolate the details.

1624
00:43:40,880 --> 00:43:42,920
Watch the point cloud slowly build.

1625
00:43:43,120 --> 00:43:45,120
When your model inevitably collapses

1626
00:43:45,320 --> 00:43:46,000
into a board cube,

1627
00:43:46,200 --> 00:43:48,160
interrogate your capture strategy.

1628
00:43:48,360 --> 00:43:50,280
Did you capture too much blank sky?

1629
00:43:50,480 --> 00:43:53,480
Did you break the chronological chain by filming a dog?

1630
00:43:53,680 --> 00:43:57,480
The trial and error fundamentally changes how you perceive physical space.

1631
00:43:57,680 --> 00:44:02,480
You will never look at a blank white wall or a heavily textured stone carving the same way again.

1632
00:44:02,680 --> 00:44:04,200
It really rewires your brain.

1633
00:44:04,400 --> 00:44:09,000
It does. Now I want to leave you with a final lingering thought that builds on this entire discussion.

1634
00:44:09,200 --> 00:44:11,240
The core strength of Schoenberger's collection

1635
00:44:11,440 --> 00:44:15,320
mapper is that it does not need a drone, it does not need a top down grid,

1636
00:44:15,480 --> 00:44:17,880
and it does not need RTK GPS.

1637
00:44:18,080 --> 00:44:23,360
It was explicitly designed to handle the messy, random, overlapping reality of human photography.

1638
00:44:23,560 --> 00:44:25,920
It thrives on unstructured collections.

1639
00:44:26,120 --> 00:44:29,800
So consider the implications of scaling that capability.

1640
00:44:30,000 --> 00:44:34,120
What happens if we take this software and instead of feeding it a thousand photos

